---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="From Robot Runtime to Climate Sensor — OpenCastor Blog"
  description="How the OpenCastor runtime layer turns any idle robot into a distributed science node — and how contributor fleets tune the optimal agent harness for every hardware profile."
  ogUrl="https://opencastor.com/blog/contribute-to-science"
>

<main>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="page-hero" style="padding-bottom:24px">
    <p class="section-label reveal">Blog</p>
    <h1 class="reveal reveal-d1" style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto">From Robot Runtime to Climate Sensor:<br><span class="gradient-text">How OpenCastor Turns Idle Robots Into Science Nodes</span></h1>
    <p class="reveal reveal-d2" style="font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--text-muted);margin-top:16px">March 19, 2026 &middot; Craig Merry</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ARTICLE -->
  <section class="section" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">

      <!-- The spark -->
      <div class="wizard-tip reveal" style="margin-bottom:32px">
        <p style="font-style:italic;font-size:1.05rem;line-height:1.7;margin:0">"How long before someone launches SETI@Home but the AGI era?"</p>
        <p style="margin:8px 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          &mdash; Chris Albon (<a href="https://x.com/chrisalbon" style="color:var(--accent)">@chrisalbon</a>), Director of ML at Wikimedia Foundation<br>
          <a href="https://x.com/chrisalbon/status/2034653589755559997" style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:0.8rem">March 19, 2026</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- What is OpenCastor -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">What is OpenCastor?</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Before the feature, some context. <strong>OpenCastor is an open-source runtime layer that sits between
        a robot's hardware and its AI.</strong> It doesn't prescribe what your robot looks like. A Raspberry Pi on a desk.
        A ROS2 rover with a Jetson. A warehouse AGV running Ubuntu. An educational arm in a classroom. If it has
        a compute board and can run Python, OpenCastor can be its runtime.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        It handles what every robot needs but nobody wants to build from scratch: authentication and access control,
        safety invariants, telemetry streaming, agent harness management, skill execution, and a standardized API.
        You bring the hardware and the AI model. OpenCastor connects them safely.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The entire project is <a href="https://github.com/craigm26/OpenCastor" style="color:var(--accent)">open source on GitHub</a>.
      </p>

      <!-- RCAN -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">RCAN: The protocol robots speak</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        OpenCastor implements the <a href="https://rcan.dev" style="color:var(--accent)">RCAN specification</a> &mdash;
        the Robot Communication &amp; Authentication Network. RCAN is an open protocol that defines:
      </p>

      <div class="bento reveal" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:16px;margin-bottom:32px">
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Robot URI (RURI)</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">A canonical identifier for every robot &mdash; like a URL for physical machines. <code>rcan://registry/manufacturer/model/version/serial</code></p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Scopes &amp; Permissions</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">A hierarchy of access levels: <code>discover</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>chat</code>, <code>contribute</code>, <code>control</code>, <code>safety</code>. A guest can check status but can't drive motors.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Message Types</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Standardized commands, responses, telemetry, and safety signals &mdash; 35+ message types that work across any RCAN-compatible robot.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Safety Invariants</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Protocol-level guarantees like P66 (priority preemption) enforced in code, not prompts. Lower-priority work always yields to commands.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        RCAN is maintained by <a href="https://github.com/continuonai" style="color:var(--accent)">ContinuonAI</a>
        with reference SDKs in <a href="https://github.com/continuonai/rcan-py" style="color:var(--accent)">Python</a>
        and <a href="https://github.com/continuonai/rcan-ts" style="color:var(--accent)">TypeScript</a>.
      </p>

      <!-- Robot Registry -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The Robot Registry</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Every OpenCastor robot registers with a canonical identity. Each gets a unique RRN (Robot Resource Name),
        live telemetry streaming, and fleet-level visibility through the
        <a href="https://app.opencastor.com" style="color:var(--accent)">OpenCastor client app</a>. The registry
        is an abstraction &mdash; our reference uses Firebase Firestore, but you can back it with any database.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        This registry is what makes fleet coordination possible. You can't coordinate idle compute across robots
        if you don't know what robots exist, what hardware they have, and whether they're busy.
      </p>

      <!-- SETI@Home parallel -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The SETI@Home parallel</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        SETI@Home ran from 1999 to 2020. At its peak, 5.2 million volunteers donated their home PCs. Folding@home
        proved it could do real science during COVID-19. But both relied on humans installing software on personal
        computers. Robots are different.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        An OpenCastor robot &mdash; <em>any</em> OpenCastor robot &mdash; is already networked, already authenticated,
        already reporting telemetry. It might have a Hailo-8L doing 26 TOPS, or a Coral TPU doing 4, or a Jetson
        Orin doing 40, or just a 4-core ARM CPU. The runtime detects whatever hardware is present and profiles it
        automatically. The coordinator matches work to capability.
      </p>

      <!-- The idle compute problem -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The idle compute problem</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Robots idle. A lot. Our reference robot "Bob" idles about 20 hours a day, but that's true of most robots &mdash;
        they spend the majority of their time waiting for commands, charging, or standing by. Whatever compute
        they have goes to waste.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The raw numbers depend on fleet composition. A fleet of NPU-equipped robots contributes more raw TOPS.
        A fleet of CPU-only robots contributes less per-unit but still adds up. The point isn't any single robot's
        specs &mdash; it's that the aggregate waste across a fleet of heterogeneous robots is significant, and the
        infrastructure to coordinate it (RCAN, registry, telemetry) already exists.
      </p>

      <!-- What castor contribute does -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">What <code>castor contribute</code> does</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Enable it in your robot's config:
      </p>

      <div class="code-block reveal" style="margin-bottom:24px">
        <div class="code-header">
          <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
          <span class="code-filename">config.yaml</span>
        </div>
        <div class="code-body">
<span class="k">agent</span>:
  <span class="k">contribute</span>:
    <span class="k">enabled</span>: <span class="s">true</span>
    <span class="k">idle_after_minutes</span>: <span class="s">15</span>
    <span class="k">projects</span>:
      - <span class="s">climate</span>
      - <span class="s">biodiversity</span>
    <span class="k">coordinator</span>: <span class="s">boinc</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        After the idle threshold, the runtime contacts a coordinator (BOINC, or any service implementing the
        two-method coordinator interface), fetches a work unit, runs it on the best available hardware
        (NPU &rarr; GPU &rarr; CPU), and submits the result. The moment a real command arrives, the work unit
        is cancelled within 100ms and the robot returns to full duty.
      </p>

      <!-- Hardware agnostic -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">Hardware-agnostic by design</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The hardware profiler detects what's available and reports it to the coordinator:
      </p>

      <div class="bento reveal" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:16px;margin-bottom:32px">
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">NPU-equipped robots</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Hailo-8L (26 TOPS), Coral TPU (4 TOPS), etc. Get NPU-optimized inference work units &mdash; model scoring, classification, object detection.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">GPU-equipped robots</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Jetson Orin, CUDA GPUs. Get batch inference or training work units that leverage GPU compute.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">CPU-only robots</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Any ARM or x86 board. Get CPU-appropriate tasks &mdash; data preprocessing, lightweight inference, aggregation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Sensor-equipped robots</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Cameras, microphones, depth sensors. Could contribute situated data &mdash; BirdNET bioacoustics, species identification, environmental monitoring.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Use cases -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">Use cases</h2>

      <div class="reveal" style="margin-bottom:32px">
        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-bottom:8px">Climate Modeling</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          climateprediction.net runs ensemble climate simulations &mdash; thousands of independent models,
          embarrassingly parallel, ~15 minutes each. Perfect for robots that idle for hours.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:8px">Biodiversity Monitoring</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          Robots deployed in agricultural or conservation settings already have cameras and microphones.
          During idle time, they can run species identification inference. This is science that only makes
          sense with distributed physical sensors.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:8px">Protein Folding</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          Rosetta@home work units involve scoring protein conformations &mdash; pure matrix math that NPUs
          and GPUs excel at. Edge inference at a fraction of the power cost of data center GPUs.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:8px">Humanitarian AI</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          Medical image pre-screening for underserved regions. TB detection from chest X-rays. Edge inference
          keeps patient data local &mdash; no cloud upload required.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- P66 safety -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">Safety: P66 preemption</h2>

      <div class="wizard-tip reveal" style="margin-bottom:24px">
        <strong>Protocol 66 guarantee:</strong> Contribute work is immediately preempted by any incoming command.
        The P66 safety invariant takes absolute precedence &mdash; the robot signals <code>CONTRIBUTE_CANCEL</code>
        to the coordinator and returns to full duty within 100ms. This is enforced at the runtime level and
        cannot be disabled by configuration.
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The <code>contribute</code> scope sits at level 2.5 in the RCAN hierarchy &mdash; above <code>chat</code> (2)
        so conversation doesn't interrupt computation, but below <code>control</code> (3) so any real command
        takes immediate priority. Science gets the leftovers. In a fleet of idle robots, the leftovers add up.
      </p>

      <!-- Ecosystem -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The full ecosystem</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        What makes this different from "just run BOINC on a computer" is the integration across an open-source
        robotics stack &mdash; protocol, runtime, SDKs, client app, and registry working together:
      </p>

      <div class="reveal" style="margin-bottom:32px">
        <table class="arch-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Component</th><th>What it does</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Protocol</td><td><a href="https://rcan.dev" style="color:var(--accent)">RCAN v1.7</a></td><td><code>contribute</code> scope, 3 message types, telemetry schema</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SDKs</td><td><a href="https://github.com/continuonai/rcan-py" style="color:var(--accent)">rcan-py</a> / <a href="https://github.com/continuonai/rcan-ts" style="color:var(--accent)">rcan-ts</a></td><td>Message types, scope validation in Python &amp; TypeScript</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Runtime</td><td><code>castor/contribute/</code></td><td>Coordinator, runner, hardware profiling, fleet coordination</td></tr>
            <tr><td>API</td><td>REST endpoints</td><td><code>/api/contribute</code>, <code>/start</code>, <code>/stop</code>, <code>/history</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>CLI</td><td><code>castor contribute</code></td><td>Status, start, stop, history from terminal</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Client</td><td><a href="https://app.opencastor.com" style="color:var(--accent)">Flutter app</a></td><td>Real-time stats, enable/disable toggle, project selection</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Registry</td><td>Firestore telemetry</td><td>Live contribution stats visible across the fleet</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Hardware-specific harness optimization -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:64px;margin-bottom:16px">What's next: community-tuned harness configs</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The second act of <code>castor contribute</code> is more personal. Every robot already broadcasts its
        <code>hardware_tier</code> &mdash; <code>pi5-hailo</code>, <code>pi4-8gb</code>, <code>server</code>,
        and so on. That metadata is the missing ingredient for something genuinely useful: <strong>community-tuned
        agent harness configurations, optimized per hardware profile</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Here's the idea. When your Pi 5 + Hailo-8L robot idles, instead of (or alongside) donating to a
        science work unit, it runs harness evaluation scenarios tuned to its exact hardware combo. How aggressive
        should <code>thinking_budget</code> be when the NPU is handling inference? What <code>context_budget</code>
        saturates the memory bandwidth? What retry policy actually improves outcomes on a robot with 100ms camera
        latency? These questions have hardware-specific answers, and only a fleet of real robots can answer them.
      </p>

      <!-- Manufactured combos table -->
      <div class="reveal" style="margin:32px 0;overflow-x:auto">
        <table class="arch-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Hardware profile</th>
              <th>Key tunables explored</th>
              <th>What contributors unlock</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Pi 5 + Hailo-8L NPU</strong></td>
              <td><code>nexa_enabled</code>, <code>thinking_budget</code>, NPU model routing</td>
              <td>Optimal on-device inference split between NPU and cloud</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Pi 5 · 8 GB (no NPU)</strong></td>
              <td><code>context_budget</code>, <code>fast_model</code> selection</td>
              <td>Best local model for each task class without NPU offload</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Pi 4 · 4 GB</strong></td>
              <td><code>cost_gate_usd</code>, aggressive <code>thinking_budget</code> floor</td>
              <td>Minimal-cloud config that still produces reliable behavior</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Waveshare ALPHA</strong></td>
              <td>Arm-manipulation HITL thresholds, retry policy</td>
              <td>Consent + safety gates tuned to physical manipulation latency</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Unitree Go2</strong></td>
              <td>Gait-aware drift detection, parallel fork config</td>
              <td>Navigation harness that doesn't fight the onboard locomotion stack</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Server-class (Jetson, x86)</strong></td>
              <td>Higher <code>context_budget</code>, multi-model tiers, parallel branches</td>
              <td>Full-power harness that saturates available VRAM without waste</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The results aggregate nightly via the autoresearch pipeline. When enough contributors with a given
        hardware profile have submitted evaluation data, the pipeline's ranker finds the winning config and
        pushes it directly to the profile's champion file in the ecosystem. <strong>Robots with that hardware
        tier automatically receive the update at next sync.</strong> No manual tuning. No one-size-fits-all
        compromise.
      </p>

      <div class="wizard-tip reveal" style="margin:32px 0">
        <strong>How it will work:</strong>
        <ol style="margin:12px 0 0 0;padding-left:20px;line-height:2">
          <li>Enable <code>castor contribute</code> (opt-in, one line)</li>
          <li>Your robot's idle cycles run harness eval scenarios matched to its <code>hardware_tier</code></li>
          <li>Results feed the nightly aggregation pipeline alongside other contributors with the same hardware</li>
          <li>The winning harness config for your hardware profile propagates back to your robot automatically</li>
          <li>Your contribution stats show which harness improvements your robot helped discover</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        This is the flywheel. More contributors → more hardware-specific data → better harness configs for
        everyone with that hardware → easier to get good results out of the box → more people adopt
        OpenCastor → more contributors. The research pipeline was always going to improve the default harness.
        The fleet makes it specific.
      </p>

      <!-- Closing -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The infrastructure already exists</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Chris Albon asked how long before someone launches SETI@Home for the AGI era. The answer is: the
        infrastructure already exists. OpenCastor gives any robot a standardized runtime. RCAN gives it an
        identity and a protocol. The registry gives it fleet visibility. <code>castor contribute</code> is just
        the natural consequence &mdash; if you have the infrastructure, the idle compute question answers itself.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        It's opt-in, it's safe, it's preemptible, and it's open source. Your robot was going to idle anyway.
        Might as well cure something &mdash; and tune your harness while you're at it.
      </p>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="reveal" style="margin-top:48px;padding:32px;background:var(--bg-card);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:12px;text-align:center">
        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-bottom:16px">Enable contribute on your robot</h3>
        <div class="code-block" style="max-width:400px;margin:0 auto 20px">
          <div class="code-header">
            <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
            <span class="code-filename">Terminal</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-body">castor contribute start</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center">
          <a href="/docs/contribute" class="btn btn-primary">Read the docs</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/craigm26/OpenCastor" class="btn btn-secondary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View on GitHub</a>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</main>

<style>
  .arch-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
  }
  .arch-table th {
    text-align: left;
    padding: 8px 12px;
    background: var(--alt-bg);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border);
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .arch-table td {
    padding: 8px 12px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  .arch-table tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
</style>

</BaseLayout>
